      <div xml:id="pl-l4d3c3">
        <head xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Hd1e109">CAP. III</head>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-d1e112">
          Nevertheless it is read in the 
          Legitur tamen in 
          <ref xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Rd1e116" corresp="#pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e122"><title>Acts of the Apostles</title></ref>,
          that the Apostles baptized 
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e122" source="http://scta.info/resource/act8_12">in the name of Christ</quote>
            <bibl>Actus 8:12</bibl>
          </cit>; 
          but in this name, as 
          <ref xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Rd1e129" corresp="#pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e114"><name>Ambrose</name></ref> 
          explains,
          the entire trinity is understood: 
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e114">
              For it is understood, 
              when you say Christ, 
              both Father, by which he was anointed,
              and he who has been anointed, 
              and the Holy Spirit, 
              through whom he was anointed
            </quote>
            <bibl>Ambrosius, De spiritu sancto, I, c. 3., n. 44 (PL 16:745)</bibl>
          </cit>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-d1e118">
          Whence  
          <ref xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Rd1e142" corresp="#pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e120"><name>Pope Nicolas</name></ref> : 
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e120" source="http://scta.info/resource/gd-p3d4-d1e470">
              You are asserting that many were baptized 
              by a certain Jew, 
              you ask what then should be done,
              these ones are surely baptized, 
              if they were baptized in the name of the Holy Trinity,
              or
              <quote xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e150" source="http://scta.info/resource/act8_12">in the name of Christ</quote>, 
              just as we read in the 
              <ref xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Rd1e153" corresp="#pl-l4d3c3-Qd1e150"><title>Acts of the Apostles</title></ref>,
              for they are one and the same, 
              as
              <ref xml:id="pl-l4d3c3-Rd1e157">
                holy <name ref="#Ambrose">Ambrose</name> explains
              </ref>
            </quote>
          </cit>.
        </p>
      </div>
